{"id":"2012.15154","submitter":"Olle Abrahamsson","authors":"Olle Abrahamsson, Danyo Danev, Erik G. Larsson","title":"On the Impact of Random Actions on Opinion Dynamics","comments":"7 pages. arXiv admin note: substantial text overlap with\n  arXiv:1912.04183","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.SI","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study opinion dynamics in a social network with stubborn agents who\ninfluence their neighbors but who themselves always stick to their initial\nopinion. We consider first the well-known DeGroot model. While it is known in\nthe literature that this model can lead to consensus even in the presence of a\nstubborn agent, we show that the same result holds under weaker assumptions\nthan has been previously reported. We then consider a recent extension of the\nDeGroot model in which the opinion of each agent is a random Bernoulli\ndistributed variable, and by leveraging on the first result we establish that\nthis model also leads to consensus, in the sense of convergence in probability,\nin the presence of a stubborn agent. Moreover, all agents' opinions converge to\nthat of the stubborn agent. We also consider a variation on this model where\nthe stubborn agent is replaced with a drifting agent and show that herding is\nachieved also in this case. Finally, we offer a detailed critique of a proof\nregarding a claim about a closely related model in the recent literature.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 30 Dec 2020 13:42:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-01-01"}
